{"title_page": "Drew Spence", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Drew Spence\n|image          = Drew Spence 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size     =\n|caption        = Spence in 2014 with [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]].\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1992|10|23|df=y}}\n|fullname       = \n|birth_place    = [[London]], England\n|height         = \n|position       = [[Midfielder]]\n|currentclub    = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|clubnumber     = 24\n|youthyears1    = \n|youthclubs1    = [[Arsenal L.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|youthyears2    = \n|youthclubs2    = [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]\n|years1         = 2008\u2013\n|clubs1         = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|caps1          = 88\n|goals1         = 12<!-- Soccerway only has stats from 2011 onwards -->\n|nationalyears1 = 2015\n|nationalteam1  = [[England women's national football team|England]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|club-update    = 16:00, 20 November 2018 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 14:36, 25 February 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Drew Spence''' (born 23 October 1992) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[FA WSL]] club [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]] and won two [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for the [[England women's national football team]].\n\n==Club career==\nChelsea and England teammate [[Gilly Flaherty]] recalled playing alongside Spence in the [[Arsenal L.F.C.|Arsenal]] Centre of Excellence.<ref name=\"onebyone\">{{cite news|last1=Flaherty|first1=Gilly|authorlink1=Gilly Flaherty|title=Chelsea Ladies One by One|url=http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/chelsea_ladies_one_by_one_part_two.html|accessdate=24 October 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea L.F.C.]]|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120070528/http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/chelsea_ladies_one_by_one_part_two.html|archive-date=20 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Spence progressed to [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]'s youth team, before signing for [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Randall|first1=James|title=Drew: Let\u2019s keep the Wolf from the door|url=http://www.theleaguepaper.com/latest-news/2905/drew-lets-keep-the-wolf-from-the-door/|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=The Football League Paper|date=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nChelsea reached the [[FA Women's Cup]] final for the first time in [[2012 FA Women's Cup Final|2012]], but were eventually beaten by [[Birmingham City L.F.C.|Birmingham City]] in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] after twice taking the lead in a 2\u20132 draw. Spence's effort was saved by [[Rebecca Spencer|Becky Spencer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/shootout-has-unhappy-ending-for-chelsea-ladies-7791442.html|title=Shoot-out has unhappy ending for Chelsea Ladies|accessdate=2012-05-27|date=2012-05-27|publisher=[[The Independent]]|first=John|last=Nisbet}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Chelsea won their first ever major trophy, in the [[2015 FA Women's Cup Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]]. They then beat [[Sunderland A.F.C. Ladies|Sunderland]] 4\u20130 in October 2015 to secure the [[FA WSL]] title and a League and Cup \"[[Double (association football)|double]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=WSL 1: Chelsea Ladies 4\u20130 Sunderland Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34372478|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 October 2015}}</ref> At the end of the season Spence signed a new two-year contract with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ladies Preview: Spence Seeks Solidity|url=http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/ladies_preview_spence_seeks_solidity.html|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea L.F.C.]]|date=11 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120053732/http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/ladies_preview_spence_seeks_solidity.html|archive-date=20 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring a 5&ndash;0 thrashing by [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]] in October 2018, Spence left [[Kim Little]] nursing a broken leg with what Arsenal's website described as a \"heavy tackle\". The match officials were criticised for failing to send off Spence, who left Little ruled out for around ten weeks.<ref name = \"fibula\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45879266 |title=Kim Little: Lucy Bronze criticises officials as Arsenal's Scotland midfielder fractures leg |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 Spence signed a [https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/11/spence-signs-contract-extension?cardIndex=0-0&fbclid=IwAR2qijJ8E075WfyZqQpkRcVltsXrCZolb_U5OsiLXPemFnWW622pPrfUVm8 new contract] that will see her stay with Chelsea until 2022.\n\n==International career==\n\nNational coach [[Mark Sampson]] gave Spence her first senior call up in October 2015, in an understrength squad for the [[2015 Yongchuan International Tournament]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavery|first1=Glenn|title=Laura Coombs determined to grab her England chance in China|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/womens/2015/oct/cfa-international-womens-tournament-china-australia-laura-coombs-chelsea|accessdate=24 October 2015|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref> She won her first England [[Cap (sports)|cap]] on 23 October 2015, as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in England's 2\u20131 defeat by [[China women's national football team|China]] in [[Yongchuan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=England women beaten by China despite Eniola Aluko goal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34607337|accessdate=23 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Spence's Chelsea team-mate [[Eni Aluko]] was pursuing allegations of racial discrimination against [[The FA]] through the pages of ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper. Spence was drawn into the controversy when she was revealed as the previously-anonymous \"The Player\" who was said to have been \"upset and offended\" by Mark Sampson on the trip to China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Daniel |title=FA may launch new Mark Sampson inquiry after Drew Spence intervention |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/14/fa-mark-sampson-inquiry-drew-spence-eni-aluko |accessdate=20 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSpence's [[Sibling|brother]] [[Lewwis Spence]] is himself a non-league footballer.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Luke Lambert|title=Lewwis Spence leaves Thurrock for pastures new|url=http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/sport/14525755.Spence_leaves_Thurrock_for_pastures_new/|website=Thurrock Gazette|publisher=Thurrock Gazette|accessdate=27 August 2016|date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.chelseafc.com/teams/chelsea-ladies/player-profiles/drew-spence.html Drew Spence] at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea FC]]\n* [http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players?p=347437 Drew Spence profile] at [[the Football Association]]\n*[https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/11/spence-signs-contract-extension?cardIndex=0-0&fbclid=IwAR2qijJ8E075WfyZqQpkRcVltsXrCZolb_U5OsiLXPemFnWW622pPrfUVm8 Drew Spence news] at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea FC]]\n\n{{Chelsea L.F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spence, Drew}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women's footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League players]]\n[[Category:FA Women's Super League players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. Women players]]\n[[Category:Fulham L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Greater London]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{England-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Drew Spence\n|image          = Drew Spence 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size     =\n|caption        = Spence in 2014 with [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]].\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1992|10|23|df=y}}\n|fullname       = \n|birth_place    = [[London]], England\n|height         = \n|position       = [[Midfielder]]\n|currentclub    = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|clubnumber     = 24\n|youthyears1    = \n|youthclubs1    = [[Arsenal L.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|youthyears2    = \n|youthclubs2    = [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]\n|years1         = 2008\u2013\n|clubs1         = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|caps1          = 88\n|goals1         = 12<!-- Soccerway only has stats from 2011 onwards -->\n|nationalyears1 = 2015\n|nationalteam1  = [[England women's national football team|England]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|club-update    = 16:00, 20 November 2018 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 14:36, 25 February 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Drew Spence''' (born 23 October 1992) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[FA WSL]] club [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]] and won two [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for the [[England women's national football team]].\n\n==Club career==\nChelsea and England teammate [[Gilly Flaherty]] recalled playing alongside Spence in the [[Arsenal L.F.C.|Arsenal]] Centre of Excellence.<ref name=\"onebyone\">{{cite news|last1=Flaherty|first1=Gilly|authorlink1=Gilly Flaherty|title=Chelsea Ladies One by One|url=http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/chelsea_ladies_one_by_one_part_two.html|accessdate=24 October 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea L.F.C.]]|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120070528/http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/chelsea_ladies_one_by_one_part_two.html|archive-date=20 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Spence progressed to [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]'s youth team, before signing for [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Randall|first1=James|title=Drew: Let\u2019s keep the Wolf from the door|url=http://www.theleaguepaper.com/latest-news/2905/drew-lets-keep-the-wolf-from-the-door/|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=The Football League Paper|date=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nChelsea reached the [[FA Women's Cup]] final for the first time in [[2012 FA Women's Cup Final|2012]], but were eventually beaten by [[Birmingham City L.F.C.|Birmingham City]] in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] after twice taking the lead in a 2\u20132 draw. Spence's effort was saved by [[Rebecca Spencer|Becky Spencer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/shootout-has-unhappy-ending-for-chelsea-ladies-7791442.html|title=Shoot-out has unhappy ending for Chelsea Ladies|accessdate=2012-05-27|date=2012-05-27|publisher=[[The Independent]]|first=John|last=Nisbet}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Chelsea won their first ever major trophy, in the [[2015 FA Women's Cup Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]]. They then beat [[Sunderland A.F.C. Ladies|Sunderland]] 4\u20130 in October 2015 to secure the [[FA WSL]] title and a League and Cup \"[[Double (association football)|double]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=WSL 1: Chelsea Ladies 4\u20130 Sunderland Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34372478|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 October 2015}}</ref> At the end of the season Spence signed a new two-year contract with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ladies Preview: Spence Seeks Solidity|url=http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/ladies_preview_spence_seeks_solidity.html|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea L.F.C.]]|date=11 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120053732/http://www.chelsealadiesfc.com/news/ladies_preview_spence_seeks_solidity.html|archive-date=20 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring a 5&ndash;0 thrashing by [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]] in October 2018, Spence left [[Kim Little]] nursing a broken leg with what Arsenal's website described as a \"heavy tackle\". The match officials were criticised for failing to send off Spence, who left Little ruled out for around ten weeks.<ref name = \"fibula\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45879266 |title=Kim Little: Lucy Bronze criticises officials as Arsenal's Scotland midfielder fractures leg |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 Spence signed a [https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/11/spence-signs-contract-extension?cardIndex=0-0&fbclid=IwAR2qijJ8E075WfyZqQpkRcVltsXrCZolb_U5OsiLXPemFnWW622pPrfUVm8 new contract] that will see her stay with Chelsea until 2022.\n\n==International career==\n\nNational coach [[Mark Sampson]] gave Spence her first senior call up in October 2015, in an understrength squad for the [[2015 Yongchuan International Tournament]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavery|first1=Glenn|title=Laura Coombs determined to grab her England chance in China|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/womens/2015/oct/cfa-international-womens-tournament-china-australia-laura-coombs-chelsea|accessdate=24 October 2015|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref> She won her first England [[Cap (sports)|cap]] on 23 October 2015, as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in England's 2\u20131 defeat by [[China women's national football team|China]] in [[Yongchuan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=England women beaten by China despite Eniola Aluko goal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34607337|accessdate=23 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Spence's Chelsea team-mate [[Eni Aluko]] was pursuing allegations of racial discrimination against [[The FA]] through the pages of ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper. Spence was drawn into the controversy when she was revealed as the previously-anonymous \"The Player\" who was said to have been \"upset and offended\" by Mark Sampson on the trip to China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Daniel |title=FA may launch new Mark Sampson inquiry after Drew Spence intervention |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/14/fa-mark-sampson-inquiry-drew-spence-eni-aluko |accessdate=20 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSpence's [[Sibling|brother]] [[Lewwis Spence]] is himself a non-league footballer.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Luke Lambert|title=Lewwis Spence leaves Thurrock for pastures new|url=http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/sport/14525755.Spence_leaves_Thurrock_for_pastures_new/|website=Thurrock Gazette|publisher=Thurrock Gazette|accessdate=27 August 2016|date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.chelseafc.com/teams/chelsea-ladies/player-profiles/drew-spence.html Drew Spence] at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea FC]]\n* [http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players?p=347437 Drew Spence profile] at [[the Football Association]]\n*[https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/11/spence-signs-contract-extension?cardIndex=0-0&fbclid=IwAR2qijJ8E075WfyZqQpkRcVltsXrCZolb_U5OsiLXPemFnWW622pPrfUVm8 Drew Spence news] at [[Www.chelseafc.com|Chelsea FC]]\n\n{{Chelsea L.F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spence, Drew}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women's footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League players]]\n[[Category:FA Women's Super League players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. Women players]]\n[[Category:Fulham L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Greater London]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{England-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "McOREAL", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Spence"}
{"title_page": "Classifications of snow", "text_new": "{{short description|Methods for describing snowfall events and the resulting snow crystals}}\n{{broader|Snow}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:Snow packed trees.jpg|thumb|right|Snow accumulation on ground and in tree branches in [[Germany]]]]\n[[File:Snow blowing.jpg|thumb|Snow blowing across a highway in [[Canada]]]]\n[[File:Diapo1977-07 37 Au pic de l'Etendard.jpg|thumb|Spring snow on a mountain in [[France]]]]\n'''Classifications of snow''' describe and categorize the attributes of [[snow]]-generating weather events, including the individual crystals both in the air and on the ground, and the deposited snow pack as it changes over time. Snow can be classified by describing the [[Winter storm|weather event]] that is producing it, the shape of its [[ice crystals]] or [[Snowflake|flakes]], how it collects on the ground, and thereafter how it changes form and composition. Depending on the status of the snow in the air or on the ground, a different classification applies.\n\nSnowfall arises from a variety of events that vary in intensity and cause, subject to classification by weather bureaus. Some snowstorms are part of a larger weather pattern. Other snowfall occurs from [[Lake-effect snow|lake effects]] or atmospheric instability near mountains. Falling snow takes many different forms, depending on atmospheric conditions, especially vapor content and temperature, as it falls to the ground. Once on the ground, snow crystals metamorphose into different shapes, influenced by wind, freeze-thaw and [[Sublimation (phase transition)|sublimation]]. Snow on the ground forms a variety of shapes, formed by wind and thermal processes, all subject to ''formal'' classifications both by scientists and by ski resorts. Those who work and play in snowy landscapes have ''informal'' classifications, as well.\n\nThere is a long history of northern and alpine cultures describing snow in their different languages, including [[Inupiaq language|Inupiat]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Finnish language|Finnish]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pruitt|first=William O. Jr.|date=2005|title=Why and how to study a snowcover|url=http://wilds.mb.ca/taiga/snowcoverstudy.pdf|journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist|volume=119|issue=1|pages=118\u2013128|via=|doi=10.22621/cfn.v119i1.90}}</ref> However, the lore about [[Eskimo words for snow|the multiplicity of Eskimo words for snow]] originates from controversial scholarship on a topic that's difficult to define, because of the structures of the languages involved.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.uaf.edu/anlc/snow/|title=Inuit Snow Terms: How Many and What Does It Mean?|last=Kaplan|first=Larry|date=2003|publisher=Alaska Native Language Center|language=en|location=Montreal|access-date=2 January 2019|journal=Building Capacity in Arctic Societies: Dynamics and Shifting Perspectives. Proceedings from the 2nd IPSSAS Seminar. Nunavut, Canada: May 26-June 6, 2003}}</ref>\n\n== Classification of snow events ==\nSnow events reflect the type of storm that generates them and the type of precipitation that results. Classification systems use rates of deposition, types of precipitation, visibility, duration and wind speed to characterize such events.\n\n=== Snow-producing events ===\n[[File:Snowpocalypse Holiday Blizzard 2010 Route 46 Little Ferry New Jersey.jpg|thumb|Blizzard conditions with heavy snow, high winds and reduced visibility in [[New Jersey]]]]\nThe following terms are consistent with the classifications of United States [[National Weather Service]] and the [[Meteorological Service of Canada]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/environment-climate-change/services/sky-watchers/glossary.html#wsglossaryS|title=Skywatchers weather glossary|last=Environment|first=Canada|date=10 March 2010|website=aem|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Blizzard \u2014'' [[Blizzard]]s are characterized by sustained wind or frequent gusts of {{convert|35|mph|kph|order=flip}} or greater and falling or blowing snow that frequently lowers visibility to less than  {{convert|0.25|mi|m|order=flip}} over a period of 3 hours or longer.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=b|title=Glossary: Blizzard|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>'''\n*''Cold front'' \u2014 A [[cold front]] is the leading edge of unstable cold air, replacing warmer, circulating around an [[extratropical cyclone]], which may cause instability snow showers or squalls.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Meteorology today : an introduction to weather, climate, and the environment|first=C. Donald|last=Ahrens|date=2007|publisher=Thomson/Brooks/Cole|isbn=978-0495011620|edition= 8th|location=Belmont, Calif.|pages=298\u2013300, 352|oclc=66911677}}</ref>\n*''Extratropical cyclone'' \u2014 A winter [[extratropical cyclone]] (also ''[[nor'easter|nor-easter]]'') may cause snow, especially in its northwest quadrant (in the [[Northern Hemisphere]]) where the wind comes from the northeast.<ref name=\":6\" />\n*''Lake-effect snow \u2014'' [[Lake-effect snow|Lake-effect]] or ocean-effect snow occurs when relatively cold air flows over warm lake (or ocean) water to cause localized, convective snow bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Lake-effect_snow|title=Lake-effect snow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=l|title=Glossary - Lake effect snow|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Mountain snow'' \u2014 [[Orographic lift]] causes moist air to rise upslope on mountains to where freezing temperatures cause [[Precipitation types#Orographic|orographic snow]].\n*''Snow flurry \u2014'' [[Snow flurry|Snow flurries]] are an intermittent, light snowfall events of short duration with only a trace level of accumulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=s|title=Glossary - Snow flurry|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Snowsquall'' \u2014 [[Snowsquall]]s are brief, but intense periods of moderate to heavy snowfall with strong, gusty surface winds and measurable snowfall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=s|title=Glossary - Snow squall|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Thundersnow'' \u2014 [[Thundersnow]] occurs when a snowstorm generates lightning and thunder. It may occur in areas that are prone to a combination of wind and moisture triggers that promote instability, often downwind of lakes or in mountainous terrain. It may occur with intensifying extratropical cyclones. Such events are often associated with intense snowfall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Thundersnow|title=Thundersnow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Warm front'' \u2014 Snow may fall as warm air initially over-rides cold in a [[warm front]], circulating around an extratropical cyclone.<ref name=\":6\" />\n*''Winter storm'' \u2014 [[Winter storm]]s may constitute any combination of sleet, snow, ice, and wind that accumulates {{convert|7|in|cm|order=flip}} or more of snow in 12 hours or less; or {{convert|9|in|cm|order=flip}} or more in 24 hours or {{convert|0.5|in|cm|order=flip}} of ice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/bgm/WinterTerms|title=National Weather Service Expanded Winter Weather Terminology|last=US Department of Commerce|first=NOAA|website=www.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Precipitation ===\n[[File:Bentley snowflake micrograph no. 777.jpg|thumb|right|Wilson Bentley micrograph showing two classes of snow crystals, plate and column.]]\n[[File:Snowflake 300um LTSEM, 13368.jpg|right|thumb|Snow crystal with a column capped with plates, which are growing rime ice.]]\nPrecipitation may be characterized by type and intensity.\n\n====Type====\nFrozen precipitation includes snow, snow pellets, snow grains, ice crystals, ice pellets, and hail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Frozen_precipitation|title=Frozen precipitation - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Falling snow comprises ice crystals, growing in a hexagonal pattern and combining as snowflakes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow|title=Snow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Ice crystals may be \"any one of a number of macroscopic, crystalline forms in which ice appears, including hexagonal columns, hexagonal platelets, dendritic crystals, ice needles, and combinations of these forms\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Ice_crystals|title=Ice crystal - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref> Terms that refer to falling snow particles include:\n* ''Ice crystal'' \u2014 Ice crystals (also ''[[diamond dust]]'') are manifest suspended in the atmosphere as needles, columns or plates at very low temperatures in a stable atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=i|title=Glossary - ice crystal|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Ice pellet'' \u2014 Ice pellets have two manifestations, ''sleet'' and ''small hail'', that result in irregular spherical particles, which typically bounce upon impact. Sleet comprises grains of ice that form from refreezing of largely melted snowflakes when falling through into a frozen layer of air near the surface. Small hail forms from snow pellets encased in a thin layer of ice caused either by accretion of droplets or by refreezing of each particle's surface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Ice_pellets|title=Ice pellets - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Hail'' \u2014 [[Hail]] forms in cumulonimbus clouds as irregular spheres of ice (''hailstones'') with a diameter of 5&nbsp;mm or more.\n* ''Snowflake'' \u2014 A [[snowflake]] grows from a single ice crystal and may have agglomerated with other crystals as it falls.<ref name=\"Knights\">Knight, C.; Knight, N.  (1973). Snow crystals. Scientific American, vol. 228, no. 1, pp. 100\u2013107.</ref>\n* ''Snow grain'' \u2014 Snow grains (also ''granular snow'') consist of flattened and elongated agglomerations of crystals, typically less than 1-mm diameter, that include a range of crystal sizes and complexities to include a rime core and glaze coating. They typically originate in stratus clouds or from fog and fall in small quantities, not in showers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_grains|title=Snow grains - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Snow pellet'' \u2014 [[Graupel|Snow pellets]] (also ''soft hail'', ''graupel'', ''tapioca snow'') consist of spherical or conical ice particles, based on a snowlike structure,  with diameters between 2&nbsp;mm and 5&nbsp;mm. They form by accretion of supercooled droplets near or slightly below the freezing point and rebound off a hard surfaces upon landing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_pellets|title=Snow pellets - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Intensity====\nIn the US, the intensity of snowfall is characterized by visibility through the falling precipitation, as follows:<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Light snow'': visibility of {{convert|1|km|yds}} or greater\n*''Moderate snow'': visibility between {{convert|1|km|yds}} and {{convert|0.5|km|yds}}\n*''Heavy snow'': visibility of less than {{convert|0.5|km|yds}}\n\n==Snow crystal classification==\n[[File:Snowflakeschapte00warriala-p11-p21-p29-p39.jpg|thumb|right|An early classification of snowflakes by [[Israel Perkins Warren]].<ref>{{cite book\n | last =  Warren\n | first =  Israel Perkins\n | author-link = Israel Perkins Warren\n | title = Snowflakes: a chapter from the book of nature\n | publisher = American Tract Society\n | date = 1863\n | location = Boston\n | pages = 164\n | language =\n | url = https://archive.org/details/snowflakeschapte00warriala\n | access-date = 25 November 2016}}</ref>]]\n{{Main|Snowflake#Classification}}\nIce approximates [[hexagon]]al symmetry in most of its atmospheric manifestations of a [[Crystal structure|crystal]] lattice as snow. Temperature and [[Vapour pressure of water|vapor pressure]] determine the growth of the [[Hexagonal crystal family|hexagonal crystal]] lattice in different forms that include columnar growth in the axis perpendicular to the hexagonal plane to form snow crystals.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Ukichiro Nakaya]] developed a crystal morphology diagram, relating crystal shape to the temperature and moisture conditions under which they formed.<ref name=Snowenclyclopedia>{{Cite book\n |first            = Michael P.\n |last             = Bishop\n |first2           = Helgi\n |last2            = Bj\u00f6rnsson\n |first3           = Wilfried\n |last3            = Haeberli\n |first4           = Johannes\n |last4            = Oerlemans\n |first5           = John F.\n |last5            = Shroder\n |first6           = Martyn\n |last6            = Tranter\n |editor-last      = Singh\n |editor-first     = Vijay P.\n |editor2-last     = Singh\n |editor2-first    = Pratap\n |editor3-last     = Haritashya\n |editor3-first    = Umesh K.\n |year             = 2011\n |pages            = 1253\n |isbn             = 978-90-481-2641-5\n |title            = Encyclopedia of Snow, Ice and Glaciers\n |publisher        = Springer Science & Business Media\n |url              = https://books.google.com/books?id=mKKtQR4T-1MC\n }}</ref> Magono and Lee devised a classification of freshly formed snow crystals that includes 80 distinct shapes. They are summarized in the following principal snow crystal categories (with symbol):<ref name = magono-lee>{{Cite journal\n | last = Magono\n | first = Choji\n | author-link =\n | last2 = Lee\n | first2 = Chung Woo\n | title = Meteorological Classification of Natural Snow Crystals\n | place = Hokkaido\n | journal = Journal of the Faculty of Science\n | volume = 3\n | issue = 4\n | date = 1966\n | edition = Geophysics\n | series = 7\n | url =\n | pages = 321\u2013335\n | language = English\n | hdl = 2115/8672\n }}</ref>\n*''Needle'' (N): Snow crystals may be simple or a combination of needles.\n*''Column'' (C): Snow crystals may be simple or a combination of columns.\n*''Plate'' (P): Snow crystals may be a regular crystal in one plane, a plane crystal with extensions ([[Dendrite (crystal)|dendrites]]), a crystal with irregular number of branches, crystal with 12 branches, malformed crystal, radiating assemblage of plane branches.\n*''Column and plate combination'' (CP): Snow crystals may be a column with plane crystal at both ends, a bullet with plane crystals, a plane crystal with spatial extensions at ends.\n*''Side plane'' (S): Snow crystals may have extended side planes, some scalelike side planes,  and some a combination of side planes, bullets, and columns.\n*''Rime'' (R): Rimed crystals may be densely rimed crystals, graupellike crystals, or graupel.\n*''Irregular'' (I): Snow crystals include ice particles, rimed particles, broken pieces from a crystal, and miscellaneous crystals.\n*''Germ'' (G): Crystals may be a minute column, hexagonal plate, stellar crystal, assemblage of plates, irregular germ, or other skeletal form.\n\n==Classifications of snow on the ground==\nClassification of snow on the ground comes from two sources: the science community and the community of those who encounter it in their daily lives. Snow on the ground exists both as a material with varying properties and as a variety of structures, shaped by wind, sun, temperature, and precipitation.\n[[File:Skiing Christmas '05 034.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hoar frost]] on the snow surface from crystallized water vapor emerging on a cold, clear night]]\n[[File:Cornice Aiguille de Bionassay.jpg|thumb|Cornice on an alp in [[France]]]]\n[[File:SnowHidcoteBartrimColemansHill201803020852.jpg|thumb|Snowdrift in [[Gloucestershire]]]]\n[[File:Sastrugi.jpg|thumb|Sastrugi in [[Norway]]]]\n[[File:Firn field on the top of S\u00e4uleck.jpg|thumb|Alpine firn in [[Austria]]]]\n[[File:Planetary Analogue.jpg|thumb|Penitentes under the night sky of the [[Atacama Desert]]]]\n[[File:Snow field near Gibby Beam - geograph.org.uk - 1182123.jpg|thumb|Suncups in [[England]]]]\n[[File:Giant snowball Oxford.jpg|thumb|Packing snow being rolled into a large snowball in [[Oxford, England]].]]\n\n===Classification of snowpack material properties===\nThe ''International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground'' describes snow crystal classification, once it is deposited on the ground, that include grain shape and grain size. The system also characterizes the snowpack, as the individual crystals metamorphize and coalesce.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\">{{Citation|last=Fierz|first=C.|title=The International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf|volume=83|pages=80|year=2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160929205922/http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf|url-status=live|series=IHP-VII Technical Documents in Hydrology|place=Paris|publisher=UNESCO|access-date=25 November 2016|display-authors=5|archivedate=29 September 2016|last2=Armstrong|first2=R.L.|last3=Durand|first3=Y.|last4=Etchevers|first4=P.|last5=Greene|first5=E.|last6=McClung|first6=D.M.|last7=Nishimura|first7=K.|last8=Satyawali|first8=P.K.|last9=Sokratov|first9=S.A.}}</ref> It uses the following characteristics (with units) to describe deposited snow: microstructure, grain shape, grain size (mm), snow density (kg/m<sup>3</sup>), snow hardness, liquid water content, snow temperature (\u00b0C), impurities (mass fraction), and layer thickness (cm). The grain shape is further characterized, using the following categories (with code): precipitation particles (PP), machine-made snow (MM), decomposing and fragmented precipitation particles (DF), rounded grains (RG), faceted crystals (FC), depth hoar (DH), surface hoar (SH), melt forms (MF), and ice formations (IF). Other measurements and characteristics are used as well, including a snow profile of a vertical section of the snowpack.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" /> Some snowpack features include:\n\n*''Crust'' \u2014 A variety of processes can create a crust, a layer of snow on the surface of the snowpack that is stronger than the snow below, which may be powder snow. Crusts often result from partial melting of the snow surface by direct sunlight or warm air followed by re-freezing, but can also be created by wind or by surface water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_crust|title=Snow crust - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|language=en|access-date=2 September 2018}}</ref>  Snow travelers consider the thickness and resulting strength of a crust to determine whether it is \"unbreakable\", meaning that they will support the weight of the traveler or \"breakable\", meaning that it will not.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TOADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=breakable+crust+skiing#v=onepage&q=breakable%20crust%20skiing&f=false|title=Become a backcountry expert|last=Tejada-Flores|first=Lito|date=December 1982|publisher=Backpacker|isbn=|location=|pages=28\u201334|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Depth hoar'' \u2014 [[Depth hoar]] comprises faceted snow crystals, usually poorly or completely unbonded (unsintered) to adjacent crystals, creating a weak zone in the snowpack.  Depth hoar forms from metamorphism of the snowpack in response to a large temperature gradient between the warmer ground beneath the snowpack and the surface.  The relatively high porosity (percentage of air space), relatively warm temperature (usually near freezing point), and unbonded weak snow in this layer can allow various organisms to live in it.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" />\n*''Machine-made'' \u2014 Machine-made [[Snowmaking|artificial snow]] has two classifications: round, polycrystalline particles, which are produced by the freezing of water droplets expelled from a snow cannon, and shard-like ice plates, which are produced by the shaving of ice.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" />\n*''Surface hoar'' \u2014 Surface hoar is manifest as striated, usually flat, sometimes needle-like crystals, usually deposited as [[frost]] on a snow surface that is colder than the air. Crystals grow rapidly by transfer of moisture from the atmosphere onto the snow surface, which is cooled below ambient temperature by radiational cooling.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" /> Subsequent snowfall can bury layers of surface hoar, incorporating them into the snowpack where they can form a weak layer.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Classifications of snowpack surface and structure ===\nIn addition to having material properties, snowpacks have structure which can be characterized. These properties are primarily determined through the actions of wind, sun, and temperature. Such structures have been described by mountaineers and others encountering frozen landscapes, as follows:<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GwyXx4DzDjwC&pg=PA546&dq=snow+cornice+formation#v=onepage&q=snow%20cornice%20formation&f=false|title=Mountaineering: The Freedom of the Hills|last=The Mountaineers|date=25 August 2010|publisher=Mountaineers Books|isbn=9781594854088|editor-last=Eng|editor-first=Ronald C.|location=Seattle|pages=540\u20138|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Wind-induced ====\n*''Cornice'' \u2014 Wind blowing over a ridge can create a compacted [[snowdrift]] with an overhanging top, called a [[Snow cornice|cornice]]. Cornices present a hazard to mountaineers, because they are prone to break off.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*''Finger drift'' \u2014 A finger drift is a narrow snow drift (30&nbsp;cm to 1 metre in width) crossing a roadway.  Several finger drifts in succession resemble the fingers of a hand.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6T_pCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=%22William+Kittredge%22+finger+drift+snow#v=onepage&q=%22William%20Kittredge%22%20finger%20drift%20snow&f=false|title=Home Ground: Language for an American Landscape|last=Lopez|first=Barry|last2=Gwartney|first2=Debra|date=14 April 2011|publisher=Trinity University Press|isbn=9781595340887|location=|pages=136|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Pillow drift'' \u2014 A pillow drift is a snow drift crossing a roadway and usually 3 to 4.5 metres (10\u201315 feet) in width and 30&nbsp;cm to 90&nbsp;cm (1\u20133 feet) in depth.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iORiDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&dq=%22pillow+drift%22+snow#v=onepage&q=%22pillow%20drift%22%20snow&f=false|title=Canada, I Love You: The Canadian Dream|last=Avery|first=Martin|date=2 February 2016|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781329874862|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Sastrugi'' \u2014 [[Sastrugi]] are snow surface features sculpted by wind into ridges and grooves up to 3 meters high,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lJd8_owUxFEC&pg=PA297&dq=Sastrugi#v=onepage&q=Sastrugi&f=false|title=The Antarctic Dictionary: A Complete Guide to Antarctic English|last=Hince|first=Bernadette|date=2000|publisher=Csiro Publishing|isbn=9780957747111|location=|pages=297|language=en}}</ref> with the ridges facing into the prevailing wind.<ref name=\"perpendicular\">{{Cite journal|last1=Leonard|first1=K. C.|last2=Tremblay|first2=B.|date=Dec 2006|title=Depositional origin of snow sastrugi|url=|journal=AGU Fall Meeting Abstracts|volume=2006|pages=C21C\u20131170|bibcode=2006AGUFM.C21C1170L|id=#C21C-1170|via=}}</ref>\n*''Snowdrift'' \u2014 [[Snowdrift]]s are wind-driven accumulations of snow deposited downwind of obstructions.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtmTku6p_gIC&pg=PA196&dq=snow+drift#v=onepage&q=snow%20drift&f=false|title=Snow Engineering V: Proceedings of the Fifth International Conference on Snow Engineering, 5-8 July 2004, Davos, Switzerland|last=Bartelt|first=P.|last2=Adams|first2=E.|last3=Christen|first3=M.|last4=Sack|first4=R.|last5=Sato|first5=A.|date=15 June 2004|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9789058096340|location=|pages=193\u20138|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Wind crust'' \u2014 A layer of relatively stiff, hard snow formed by deposition of wind blown snow on the windward side of a ridge or other sheltered area.  Wind crusts generally bond better to snowpack layers below and above them than wind slabs.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f41x2ObCqW0C&pg=PA138&dq=wind+slab#v=onepage&q=wind%20slab&f=false|title=Backcountry Avalanche Safety: Skiers, Climbers, Boarders, Snowshoers|last=Daffern|first=Tony|date=14 September 2009|publisher=Rocky Mountain Books Ltd|isbn=9781897522547|location=|pages=138|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Wind slab'' \u2014 A layer of relatively stiff, hard snow formed by deposition of wind blown snow on the leeward side of a ridge or other sheltered area.  Wind slabs can form over weaker, softer freshly fallen powder snow, creating an avalanche hazard on steep slopes.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Sun or temperature-induced ====\n\n*''Firn'' \u2014 [[Firn]] is dense, granular snow, which has been in place for multiple years but which has not yet consolidated into [[Glacier#Formation|glacial ice]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_pCGDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&dq=firn+The+Physics+of+Glaciers#v=onepage&q=firn%20The%20Physics%20of%20Glaciers&f=false|title=The Physics of Glaciers|last=Paterson|first=W. S. B.|date=31 January 2017|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9781483293738|language=en}}</ref>\n*N\u00e9v\u00e9 \u2014 [[N\u00e9v\u00e9]] is a young, granular type of [[snow]] which has been partially melted, refrozen and compacted, yet precedes the form of ice.  This type of snow is associated with [[glacier]] formation through the process of [[nivation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.hofstra.edu/j_b_bennington/33notes/glaciers.html|title=Geol 33 Environmental Geomorphology|publisher=Hofstra University|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> N\u00e9v\u00e9 that survives a full season of [[ablation]] turns into [[firn]], which is both older and slightly denser.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*''Penitentes'' \u2014 [[Penitente (snow formation)|Penitentes]] are snow formations, found at high elevations, which form of elongated, thin blades of hardened snow or ice up to 5 meters in height, closely spaced and pointing towards the general direction of the sun. They are evolved suncups.<ref name=\"Lliboutry2\">{{cite journal|last1=Lliboutry|first1=L.|year=1954b|title=The origin of penitentes|url=|journal=Journal of Glaciology|volume=2|issue=15|pages=331\u2013338|doi=10.1017/S0022143000025181|accessdate=|bibcode=1954JGlac...2..331L|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*''Suncups'' \u2014 [[Suncup (snow)|Suncups]] are polygonal depressions in a [[snow]] surface that form patterns with sharp narrow ridges separating smoothly concave quasi-periodic hollows. They form during the [[ablation]] (melting away) of snow from [[Solar gain|incident solar radiation]] in bright [[Sunlight|sunny conditions]], sometimes enhanced by the insulating presence of dirt along the ridges.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R_Q6j8wsVqcC&pg=PA65&dq=%22sun+cups%22+snow#v=onepage&q=%22sun%20cups%22%20snow&f=false|title=Glaciers|last=Knight|first=Peter|date=13 May 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134982240|location=|pages=65|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Yukimarimo'' \u2014 [[Yukimarimo]] are balls of fine [[frost]], formed at low temperatures on the [[Antarctic Plateau]] during light or calm winds.<ref name=\"Kameda2007\">\n{{Cite journal\n|author =  T. Kameda\n|title = Discovery and reunion with yukimarimo\n|journal = Seppyo (Journal of Japanese Society of Snow and Ice)\n|year = 2007\n|volume = 69\n|number = 3\n|pages = 403\u2013407\n|url = http://homepage3.nifty.com/takaokameda/en/Kameda2007-AboutYukimarimo-inSeppyo.pdf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Ski resort classification===\nSki resorts use standardized terminology to describe their snow conditions. In North America terms include:<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7-HCBlUw6EMC&pg=PA26&dq=Packed+powder+snow#v=onepage&q=Packed%20powder%20snow&f=false|title=Handy Facts|last=Staff|date=January 1975|publisher=Ski|isbn=|location=|pages=42|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*''Base snow'' \u2014 Base snow refers to snow that has been thoroughly consolidated.\n*''Frozen granular'' \u2014 Frozen granular is snow whose granules have frozen together.\n*''Loose granular'' \u2014 Loose granular is snow with uncohesive granules.\n*''Machine-made'' \u2014 Machine-made snow is that produce by snow cannons and is typically denser than natural snow.\n*''New snow'' \u2014 New snow is that which has fallen since the previous day's report.\n*''Packed powder'' \u2014 Packed powder is powder snow that has been compressed by [[Snow grooming|grooming]] or by ski traffic.\n*''Powder'' \u2014 Powder is freshly fallen, uncompacted snow. The density and moisture content of powder snow can vary widely; snowfall in coastal regions and areas with higher humidity is usually heavier than a similar depth of snowfall in an arid or continental region. Light, dry (low moisture content, typically 4\u20137% water content) powder snow is prized by skiers and snowboarders.<ref name=\":5\" /> It is often found in the [[Rocky Mountains]] of North America and in most regions in Japan.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Spring conditions \u2014 Spring conditions describe a variety of melting snow surfaces, including mushy powder or granular snow, which refreeze at night.\n*''Wet'' \u2014 Wet refers to warm snow with a high moisture content.\n\n===Informal classification===\nSkiers and others living with snow provide informal terms for snow conditions that they encounter.\n*''Corn snow'' \u2014 Corn snow is coarse, granular snow, subject to freeze-thaw.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*''Crud'' \u2014 Crud covers varieties of snow that all but advanced skiers find impassable. Subtypes are (a) windblown powder with irregularly shaped crust patches and ridges, (b) heavy tracked spring snow re-frozen to leave a deeply rutted surface strewn with loose blocks, (c) a deep layer of heavy snow saturated by rain (although this may go by another term).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k-o-HmRiEFAC&pg=PA106&dq=crud+snow#v=onepage&q=crud%20snow&f=false|title=Crud: Stay light and centered on the edge|last=Delaney|first=Brian|date=January 1998|publisher=Snow Country|isbn=|location=|pages=106|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Packing snow'' \u2014 Packing snow is at or near the melting point, so that it can easily be packed into snowballs and thrown or used in the construction of a snowman, or a [[snow fort]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=How to build an igloo: And other snow shelters|last=Yankielun|first=Norbert|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Slush'' \u2014 [[Slush]] is substantially melted snow with visible water in it.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JyUXOeZzhAUC&pg=PA80&dq=Slush+snow#v=onepage&q=Slush%20snow&f=false|title=High-performance Skiing|last=Yacenda|first=John|last2=Ross|first2=Tim|date=1998|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=9780880117135|location=|pages=80\u201381|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Snirt'' \u2014 Snirt is an informal term for snow covered with dirt, especially where strong winds pick up topsoil from uncovered farm fields and blow it into nearby snowy areas. Also, dirty snow left over from plowing operations.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GwVQHza8fO8C&pg=PT119&dq=snirt+snow#v=onepage&q=snirt%20snow&f=false|title=Help! I'm Laughing and I Can't Get Up|last=Higgs|first=Liz Curtis|date=1998|publisher=HarperCollins Christian Publishing|isbn=9781418558758|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Spring snow'' \u2014 Spring snow describes a variety of temperature and moisture conditions with corn snow.<ref name=\":5\" />\n*''Watermelon snow'' \u2014 [[Watermelon snow]] is reddish pink, caused by a red-colored [[green algae]] called ''[[Chlamydomonas nivalis]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=William E. Williams|author2=Holly L. Gorton|author3=Thomas C. Vogelmann|last-author-amp=yes|date=21 January 2003|title=Surface gas-exchange processes of snow algae|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]]|volume=100|issue=2|pages=562\u2013566|bibcode=2003PNAS..100..562W|doi=10.1073/pnas.0235560100|pmc=141035|pmid=12518048}}</ref>\n\n==Other cultures==\n{{See also|Eskimo words for snow}}\nThe claim that [[Eskimo\u2013Aleut languages|Eskimoan languages]] (specifically, [[Yupik languages|Yupik]] and [[Inuit languages|Inuit]]) have an unusually large number of words for \"[[snow]]\", has been attributed to the work of [[anthropologist]] [[Franz Boas]].  Boas, who lived among Baffin islanders and learnt their language, reportedly included \"only words representing meaningful distinctions\" in his account.<ref name = \"Robson\"/> A 2010 study follows the sometimes questionable scholarship regarding the question whether Eskimo languages have many more [[root word]]s for \"snow\" than the English language.<ref>{{Citation\n | first = Igor\n | last = Krupnik\n | author-link =\n | first2 = Ludger \n | last2 = M\u00fcller-Wille\n | author2-link =\n | editor-last = Krupnik\n | editor-first = Igor\n | editor2-last = Aporta\n | editor2-first = Claudio\n | editor3-last = Gearheard\n | editor3-first = Shari\n | editor4-last = Laidler\n | editor4-first = Gita J.\n | editor5-last = Holm\n | editor5-first = Lene Kielsen\n | contribution = Franz Boas and Inuktitut Terminology for Ice and Snow: From the Emergence of the Field to the \u201cGreat Eskimo Vocabulary Hoax\u201d\n | contribution-url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226206215_Franz_Boas_and_Inuktitut_Terminology_for_Ice_and_Snow_From_the_Emergence_of_the_Field_to_the_Great_Eskimo_Vocabulary_Hoax\n | series =\n | year = 2010\n | pages = 377\u201399\n | place = Berlin\n | publisher = Springer Science & Business Media\n | title = SIKU: Knowing Our Ice: Documenting Inuit Sea Ice Knowledge and Use\n | doi =\n | isbn = 9789048185870}}.</ref><ref name=\"Robson\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg21628962-800-are-there-really-50-eskimo-words-for-snow/|title=Are there really 50 Eskimo words for snow?|last=Robson|first=David|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref>\n\nStudies of the [[Sami languages]] of Norway, Sweden and Finland, conclude that the languages have anywhere from 180 snow-and-ice-related words and as many as 300 different words for [[types of snow]], tracks in snow, and conditions of the use of snow.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Magga|first=Ole Henrik|date=March 2006|title=Diversity in Saami terminology for reindeer, snow, and ice|journal=International Social Science Journal|volume=58|issue=187|pages=25\u201334|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2451.2006.00594.x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berit|first=Inga|last2=\u00d6je|first2=Danell|title=Traditional ecological knowledge among Sami reindeer herders in northern Sweden about vascular plants grazed by reindeer|url=https://septentrio.uit.no/index.php/rangifer/article/viewFile/2233/2079|journal=Rangifer|volume=32|issue=1|pages=1\u201317|via=|doi=10.7557/2.32.1.2233|year=2013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|Glacier}}\n* {{annotated link|Ice}}\n* {{annotated link|METAR}} \u2014 a format for reporting weather information\n* {{annotated link|The wrong type of snow}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.canadianfieldnaturalist.ca/index.php/cfn/article/download/90/90.pdf Why and How to Study a Snowcover] \u2013 contains an extensive taxonomy of show terminology borrowed from Inuit and some other languages\n* Fierz, C., Armstrong, R.L., Durand, Y., Etchevers, P., Greene, E., McClung, D.M., Nishimura, K., Satyawali, P.K. and Sokratov, S.A.; [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf The International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground]. IHP-VII Technical Documents in Hydrology N\u00b083, IACS Contribution N\u00b01, UNESCO-IHP, Paris, 2009.\n\n[[Category:Snow|*]]\n[[Category:Precipitation]]\n[[Category:Forms of water]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Methods for describing snowfall events and the resulting snow crystals}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:Snow packed trees.jpg|thumb|right|Snow accumulation on ground and in tree branches in [[Germany]]]]\n[[File:Snow blowing.jpg|thumb|Snow blowing across a highway in [[Canada]]]]\n[[File:Diapo1977-07 37 Au pic de l'Etendard.jpg|thumb|Spring snow on a mountain in [[France]]]]\n'''Classifications of snow''' describe and categorize the attributes of [[snow]]-generating weather events, including the individual crystals both in the air and on the ground, and the deposited snow pack as it changes over time. Snow can be classified by describing the [[Winter storm|weather event]] that is producing it, the shape of its [[ice crystals]] or [[Snowflake|flakes]], how it collects on the ground, and thereafter how it changes form and composition. Depending on the status of the snow in the air or on the ground, a different classification applies.\n\nSnowfall arises from a variety of events that vary in intensity and cause, subject to classification by weather bureaus. Some snowstorms are part of a larger weather pattern. Other snowfall occurs from [[Lake-effect snow|lake effects]] or atmospheric instability near mountains. Falling snow takes many different forms, depending on atmospheric conditions, especially vapor content and temperature, as it falls to the ground. Once on the ground, snow crystals metamorphose into different shapes, influenced by wind, freeze-thaw and [[Sublimation (phase transition)|sublimation]]. Snow on the ground forms a variety of shapes, formed by wind and thermal processes, all subject to ''formal'' classifications both by scientists and by ski resorts. Those who work and play in snowy landscapes have ''informal'' classifications, as well.\n\nThere is a long history of northern and alpine cultures describing snow in their different languages, including [[Inupiaq language|Inupiat]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Finnish language|Finnish]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pruitt|first=William O. Jr.|date=2005|title=Why and how to study a snowcover|url=http://wilds.mb.ca/taiga/snowcoverstudy.pdf|journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist|volume=119|issue=1|pages=118\u2013128|via=|doi=10.22621/cfn.v119i1.90}}</ref> However, the lore about [[Eskimo words for snow|the multiplicity of Eskimo words for snow]] originates from controversial scholarship on a topic that's difficult to define, because of the structures of the languages involved.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.uaf.edu/anlc/snow/|title=Inuit Snow Terms: How Many and What Does It Mean?|last=Kaplan|first=Larry|date=2003|publisher=Alaska Native Language Center|language=en|location=Montreal|access-date=2 January 2019|journal=Building Capacity in Arctic Societies: Dynamics and Shifting Perspectives. Proceedings from the 2nd IPSSAS Seminar. Nunavut, Canada: May 26-June 6, 2003}}</ref>\n\n== Classification of snow events ==\nSnow events reflect the type of storm that generates them and the type of precipitation that results. Classification systems use rates of deposition, types of precipitation, visibility, duration and wind speed to characterize such events.\n\n=== Snow-producing events ===\n[[File:Snowpocalypse Holiday Blizzard 2010 Route 46 Little Ferry New Jersey.jpg|thumb|Blizzard conditions with heavy snow, high winds and reduced visibility in [[New Jersey]]]]\nThe following terms are consistent with the classifications of United States [[National Weather Service]] and the [[Meteorological Service of Canada]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/environment-climate-change/services/sky-watchers/glossary.html#wsglossaryS|title=Skywatchers weather glossary|last=Environment|first=Canada|date=10 March 2010|website=aem|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Blizzard \u2014'' [[Blizzard]]s are characterized by sustained wind or frequent gusts of {{convert|35|mph|kph|order=flip}} or greater and falling or blowing snow that frequently lowers visibility to less than  {{convert|0.25|mi|m|order=flip}} over a period of 3 hours or longer.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=b|title=Glossary: Blizzard|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>'''\n*''Cold front'' \u2014 A [[cold front]] is the leading edge of unstable cold air, replacing warmer, circulating around an [[extratropical cyclone]], which may cause instability snow showers or squalls.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Meteorology today : an introduction to weather, climate, and the environment|first=C. Donald|last=Ahrens|date=2007|publisher=Thomson/Brooks/Cole|isbn=978-0495011620|edition= 8th|location=Belmont, Calif.|pages=298\u2013300, 352|oclc=66911677}}</ref>\n*''Extratropical cyclone'' \u2014 A winter [[extratropical cyclone]] (also ''[[nor'easter|nor-easter]]'') may cause snow, especially in its northwest quadrant (in the [[Northern Hemisphere]]) where the wind comes from the northeast.<ref name=\":6\" />\n*''Lake-effect snow \u2014'' [[Lake-effect snow|Lake-effect]] or ocean-effect snow occurs when relatively cold air flows over warm lake (or ocean) water to cause localized, convective snow bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Lake-effect_snow|title=Lake-effect snow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=l|title=Glossary - Lake effect snow|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Mountain snow'' \u2014 [[Orographic lift]] causes moist air to rise upslope on mountains to where freezing temperatures cause [[Precipitation types#Orographic|orographic snow]].\n*''Snow flurry \u2014'' [[Snow flurry|Snow flurries]] are an intermittent, light snowfall events of short duration with only a trace level of accumulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=s|title=Glossary - Snow flurry|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Snowsquall'' \u2014 [[Snowsquall]]s are brief, but intense periods of moderate to heavy snowfall with strong, gusty surface winds and measurable snowfall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=s|title=Glossary - Snow squall|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Thundersnow'' \u2014 [[Thundersnow]] occurs when a snowstorm generates lightning and thunder. It may occur in areas that are prone to a combination of wind and moisture triggers that promote instability, often downwind of lakes or in mountainous terrain. It may occur with intensifying extratropical cyclones. Such events are often associated with intense snowfall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Thundersnow|title=Thundersnow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Warm front'' \u2014 Snow may fall as warm air initially over-rides cold in a [[warm front]], circulating around an extratropical cyclone.<ref name=\":6\" />\n*''Winter storm'' \u2014 [[Winter storm]]s may constitute any combination of sleet, snow, ice, and wind that accumulates {{convert|7|in|cm|order=flip}} or more of snow in 12 hours or less; or {{convert|9|in|cm|order=flip}} or more in 24 hours or {{convert|0.5|in|cm|order=flip}} of ice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/bgm/WinterTerms|title=National Weather Service Expanded Winter Weather Terminology|last=US Department of Commerce|first=NOAA|website=www.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Precipitation ===\n[[File:Bentley snowflake micrograph no. 777.jpg|thumb|right|Wilson Bentley micrograph showing two classes of snow crystals, plate and column.]]\n[[File:Snowflake 300um LTSEM, 13368.jpg|right|thumb|Snow crystal with a column capped with plates, which are growing rime ice.]]\nPrecipitation may be characterized by type and intensity.\n\n====Type====\nFrozen precipitation includes snow, snow pellets, snow grains, ice crystals, ice pellets, and hail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Frozen_precipitation|title=Frozen precipitation - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Falling snow comprises ice crystals, growing in a hexagonal pattern and combining as snowflakes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow|title=Snow - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Ice crystals may be \"any one of a number of macroscopic, crystalline forms in which ice appears, including hexagonal columns, hexagonal platelets, dendritic crystals, ice needles, and combinations of these forms\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Ice_crystals|title=Ice crystal - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref> Terms that refer to falling snow particles include:\n* ''Ice crystal'' \u2014 Ice crystals (also ''[[diamond dust]]'') are manifest suspended in the atmosphere as needles, columns or plates at very low temperatures in a stable atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w1.weather.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=i|title=Glossary - ice crystal|last=National Weather Service|first=NOAA|website=w1.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''Ice pellet'' \u2014 Ice pellets have two manifestations, ''sleet'' and ''small hail'', that result in irregular spherical particles, which typically bounce upon impact. Sleet comprises grains of ice that form from refreezing of largely melted snowflakes when falling through into a frozen layer of air near the surface. Small hail forms from snow pellets encased in a thin layer of ice caused either by accretion of droplets or by refreezing of each particle's surface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Ice_pellets|title=Ice pellets - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Hail'' \u2014 [[Hail]] forms in cumulonimbus clouds as irregular spheres of ice (''hailstones'') with a diameter of 5&nbsp;mm or more.\n* ''Snowflake'' \u2014 A [[snowflake]] grows from a single ice crystal and may have agglomerated with other crystals as it falls.<ref name=\"Knights\">Knight, C.; Knight, N.  (1973). Snow crystals. Scientific American, vol. 228, no. 1, pp. 100\u2013107.</ref>\n* ''Snow grain'' \u2014 Snow grains (also ''granular snow'') consist of flattened and elongated agglomerations of crystals, typically less than 1-mm diameter, that include a range of crystal sizes and complexities to include a rime core and glaze coating. They typically originate in stratus clouds or from fog and fall in small quantities, not in showers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_grains|title=Snow grains - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Snow pellet'' \u2014 [[Graupel|Snow pellets]] (also ''soft hail'', ''graupel'', ''tapioca snow'') consist of spherical or conical ice particles, based on a snowlike structure,  with diameters between 2&nbsp;mm and 5&nbsp;mm. They form by accretion of supercooled droplets near or slightly below the freezing point and rebound off a hard surfaces upon landing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_pellets|title=Snow pellets - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Intensity====\nIn the US, the intensity of snowfall is characterized by visibility through the falling precipitation, as follows:<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Light snow'': visibility of {{convert|1|km|yds}} or greater\n*''Moderate snow'': visibility between {{convert|1|km|yds}} and {{convert|0.5|km|yds}}\n*''Heavy snow'': visibility of less than {{convert|0.5|km|yds}}\n\n==Snow crystal classification==\n[[File:Snowflakeschapte00warriala-p11-p21-p29-p39.jpg|thumb|right|An early classification of snowflakes by [[Israel Perkins Warren]].<ref>{{cite book\n | last =  Warren\n | first =  Israel Perkins\n | author-link = Israel Perkins Warren\n | title = Snowflakes: a chapter from the book of nature\n | publisher = American Tract Society\n | date = 1863\n | location = Boston\n | pages = 164\n | language =\n | url = https://archive.org/details/snowflakeschapte00warriala\n | access-date = 25 November 2016}}</ref>]]\n{{Main|Snowflake#Classification}}\nIce approximates [[hexagon]]al symmetry in most of its atmospheric manifestations of a [[Crystal structure|crystal]] lattice as snow. Temperature and [[Vapour pressure of water|vapor pressure]] determine the growth of the [[Hexagonal crystal family|hexagonal crystal]] lattice in different forms that include columnar growth in the axis perpendicular to the hexagonal plane to form snow crystals.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Ukichiro Nakaya]] developed a crystal morphology diagram, relating crystal shape to the temperature and moisture conditions under which they formed.<ref name=Snowenclyclopedia>{{Cite book\n |first            = Michael P.\n |last             = Bishop\n |first2           = Helgi\n |last2            = Bj\u00f6rnsson\n |first3           = Wilfried\n |last3            = Haeberli\n |first4           = Johannes\n |last4            = Oerlemans\n |first5           = John F.\n |last5            = Shroder\n |first6           = Martyn\n |last6            = Tranter\n |editor-last      = Singh\n |editor-first     = Vijay P.\n |editor2-last     = Singh\n |editor2-first    = Pratap\n |editor3-last     = Haritashya\n |editor3-first    = Umesh K.\n |year             = 2011\n |pages            = 1253\n |isbn             = 978-90-481-2641-5\n |title            = Encyclopedia of Snow, Ice and Glaciers\n |publisher        = Springer Science & Business Media\n |url              = https://books.google.com/books?id=mKKtQR4T-1MC\n }}</ref> Magono and Lee devised a classification of freshly formed snow crystals that includes 80 distinct shapes. They are summarized in the following principal snow crystal categories (with symbol):<ref name = magono-lee>{{Cite journal\n | last = Magono\n | first = Choji\n | author-link =\n | last2 = Lee\n | first2 = Chung Woo\n | title = Meteorological Classification of Natural Snow Crystals\n | place = Hokkaido\n | journal = Journal of the Faculty of Science\n | volume = 3\n | issue = 4\n | date = 1966\n | edition = Geophysics\n | series = 7\n | url =\n | pages = 321\u2013335\n | language = English\n | hdl = 2115/8672\n }}</ref>\n*''Needle'' (N): Snow crystals may be simple or a combination of needles.\n*''Column'' (C): Snow crystals may be simple or a combination of columns.\n*''Plate'' (P): Snow crystals may be a regular crystal in one plane, a plane crystal with extensions ([[Dendrite (crystal)|dendrites]]), a crystal with irregular number of branches, crystal with 12 branches, malformed crystal, radiating assemblage of plane branches.\n*''Column and plate combination'' (CP): Snow crystals may be a column with plane crystal at both ends, a bullet with plane crystals, a plane crystal with spatial extensions at ends.\n*''Side plane'' (S): Snow crystals may have extended side planes, some scalelike side planes,  and some a combination of side planes, bullets, and columns.\n*''Rime'' (R): Rimed crystals may be densely rimed crystals, graupellike crystals, or graupel.\n*''Irregular'' (I): Snow crystals include ice particles, rimed particles, broken pieces from a crystal, and miscellaneous crystals.\n*''Germ'' (G): Crystals may be a minute column, hexagonal plate, stellar crystal, assemblage of plates, irregular germ, or other skeletal form.\n\n==Classifications of snow on the ground==\nClassification of snow on the ground comes from two sources: the science community and the community of those who encounter it in their daily lives. Snow on the ground exists both as a material with varying properties and as a variety of structures, shaped by wind, sun, temperature, and precipitation.\n[[File:Skiing Christmas '05 034.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hoar frost]] on the snow surface from crystallized water vapor emerging on a cold, clear night]]\n[[File:Cornice Aiguille de Bionassay.jpg|thumb|Cornice on an alp in [[France]]]]\n[[File:SnowHidcoteBartrimColemansHill201803020852.jpg|thumb|Snowdrift in [[Gloucestershire]]]]\n[[File:Sastrugi.jpg|thumb|Sastrugi in [[Norway]]]]\n[[File:Firn field on the top of S\u00e4uleck.jpg|thumb|Alpine firn in [[Austria]]]]\n[[File:Planetary Analogue.jpg|thumb|Penitentes under the night sky of the [[Atacama Desert]]]]\n[[File:Snow field near Gibby Beam - geograph.org.uk - 1182123.jpg|thumb|Suncups in [[England]]]]\n[[File:Giant snowball Oxford.jpg|thumb|Packing snow being rolled into a large snowball in [[Oxford, England]].]]\n\n===Classification of snowpack material properties===\nThe ''International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground'' describes snow crystal classification, once it is deposited on the ground, that include grain shape and grain size. The system also characterizes the snowpack, as the individual crystals metamorphize and coalesce.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\">{{Citation|last=Fierz|first=C.|title=The International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf|volume=83|pages=80|year=2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160929205922/http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf|url-status=live|series=IHP-VII Technical Documents in Hydrology|place=Paris|publisher=UNESCO|access-date=25 November 2016|display-authors=5|archivedate=29 September 2016|last2=Armstrong|first2=R.L.|last3=Durand|first3=Y.|last4=Etchevers|first4=P.|last5=Greene|first5=E.|last6=McClung|first6=D.M.|last7=Nishimura|first7=K.|last8=Satyawali|first8=P.K.|last9=Sokratov|first9=S.A.}}</ref> It uses the following characteristics (with units) to describe deposited snow: microstructure, grain shape, grain size (mm), snow density (kg/m<sup>3</sup>), snow hardness, liquid water content, snow temperature (\u00b0C), impurities (mass fraction), and layer thickness (cm). The grain shape is further characterized, using the following categories (with code): precipitation particles (PP), machine-made snow (MM), decomposing and fragmented precipitation particles (DF), rounded grains (RG), faceted crystals (FC), depth hoar (DH), surface hoar (SH), melt forms (MF), and ice formations (IF). Other measurements and characteristics are used as well, including a snow profile of a vertical section of the snowpack.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" /> Some snowpack features include:\n\n*''Crust'' \u2014 A variety of processes can create a crust, a layer of snow on the surface of the snowpack that is stronger than the snow below, which may be powder snow. Crusts often result from partial melting of the snow surface by direct sunlight or warm air followed by re-freezing, but can also be created by wind or by surface water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Snow_crust|title=Snow crust - AMS Glossary|website=glossary.ametsoc.org|language=en|access-date=2 September 2018}}</ref>  Snow travelers consider the thickness and resulting strength of a crust to determine whether it is \"unbreakable\", meaning that they will support the weight of the traveler or \"breakable\", meaning that it will not.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TOADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=breakable+crust+skiing#v=onepage&q=breakable%20crust%20skiing&f=false|title=Become a backcountry expert|last=Tejada-Flores|first=Lito|date=December 1982|publisher=Backpacker|isbn=|location=|pages=28\u201334|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Depth hoar'' \u2014 [[Depth hoar]] comprises faceted snow crystals, usually poorly or completely unbonded (unsintered) to adjacent crystals, creating a weak zone in the snowpack.  Depth hoar forms from metamorphism of the snowpack in response to a large temperature gradient between the warmer ground beneath the snowpack and the surface.  The relatively high porosity (percentage of air space), relatively warm temperature (usually near freezing point), and unbonded weak snow in this layer can allow various organisms to live in it.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" />\n*''Machine-made'' \u2014 Machine-made [[Snowmaking|artificial snow]] has two classifications: round, polycrystalline particles, which are produced by the freezing of water droplets expelled from a snow cannon, and shard-like ice plates, which are produced by the shaving of ice.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" />\n*''Surface hoar'' \u2014 Surface hoar is manifest as striated, usually flat, sometimes needle-like crystals, usually deposited as [[frost]] on a snow surface that is colder than the air. Crystals grow rapidly by transfer of moisture from the atmosphere onto the snow surface, which is cooled below ambient temperature by radiational cooling.<ref name=\"Classificationonground\" /> Subsequent snowfall can bury layers of surface hoar, incorporating them into the snowpack where they can form a weak layer.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Classifications of snowpack surface and structure ===\nIn addition to having material properties, snowpacks have structure which can be characterized. These properties are primarily determined through the actions of wind, sun, and temperature. Such structures have been described by mountaineers and others encountering frozen landscapes, as follows:<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GwyXx4DzDjwC&pg=PA546&dq=snow+cornice+formation#v=onepage&q=snow%20cornice%20formation&f=false|title=Mountaineering: The Freedom of the Hills|last=The Mountaineers|date=25 August 2010|publisher=Mountaineers Books|isbn=9781594854088|editor-last=Eng|editor-first=Ronald C.|location=Seattle|pages=540\u20138|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Wind-induced ====\n*''Cornice'' \u2014 Wind blowing over a ridge can create a compacted [[snowdrift]] with an overhanging top, called a [[Snow cornice|cornice]]. Cornices present a hazard to mountaineers, because they are prone to break off.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*''Finger drift'' \u2014 A finger drift is a narrow snow drift (30&nbsp;cm to 1 metre in width) crossing a roadway.  Several finger drifts in succession resemble the fingers of a hand.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6T_pCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=%22William+Kittredge%22+finger+drift+snow#v=onepage&q=%22William%20Kittredge%22%20finger%20drift%20snow&f=false|title=Home Ground: Language for an American Landscape|last=Lopez|first=Barry|last2=Gwartney|first2=Debra|date=14 April 2011|publisher=Trinity University Press|isbn=9781595340887|location=|pages=136|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Pillow drift'' \u2014 A pillow drift is a snow drift crossing a roadway and usually 3 to 4.5 metres (10\u201315 feet) in width and 30&nbsp;cm to 90&nbsp;cm (1\u20133 feet) in depth.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iORiDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&dq=%22pillow+drift%22+snow#v=onepage&q=%22pillow%20drift%22%20snow&f=false|title=Canada, I Love You: The Canadian Dream|last=Avery|first=Martin|date=2 February 2016|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781329874862|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Sastrugi'' \u2014 [[Sastrugi]] are snow surface features sculpted by wind into ridges and grooves up to 3 meters high,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lJd8_owUxFEC&pg=PA297&dq=Sastrugi#v=onepage&q=Sastrugi&f=false|title=The Antarctic Dictionary: A Complete Guide to Antarctic English|last=Hince|first=Bernadette|date=2000|publisher=Csiro Publishing|isbn=9780957747111|location=|pages=297|language=en}}</ref> with the ridges facing into the prevailing wind.<ref name=\"perpendicular\">{{Cite journal|last1=Leonard|first1=K. C.|last2=Tremblay|first2=B.|date=Dec 2006|title=Depositional origin of snow sastrugi|url=|journal=AGU Fall Meeting Abstracts|volume=2006|pages=C21C\u20131170|bibcode=2006AGUFM.C21C1170L|id=#C21C-1170|via=}}</ref>\n*''Snowdrift'' \u2014 [[Snowdrift]]s are wind-driven accumulations of snow deposited downwind of obstructions.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtmTku6p_gIC&pg=PA196&dq=snow+drift#v=onepage&q=snow%20drift&f=false|title=Snow Engineering V: Proceedings of the Fifth International Conference on Snow Engineering, 5-8 July 2004, Davos, Switzerland|last=Bartelt|first=P.|last2=Adams|first2=E.|last3=Christen|first3=M.|last4=Sack|first4=R.|last5=Sato|first5=A.|date=15 June 2004|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9789058096340|location=|pages=193\u20138|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Wind crust'' \u2014 A layer of relatively stiff, hard snow formed by deposition of wind blown snow on the windward side of a ridge or other sheltered area.  Wind crusts generally bond better to snowpack layers below and above them than wind slabs.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f41x2ObCqW0C&pg=PA138&dq=wind+slab#v=onepage&q=wind%20slab&f=false|title=Backcountry Avalanche Safety: Skiers, Climbers, Boarders, Snowshoers|last=Daffern|first=Tony|date=14 September 2009|publisher=Rocky Mountain Books Ltd|isbn=9781897522547|location=|pages=138|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Wind slab'' \u2014 A layer of relatively stiff, hard snow formed by deposition of wind blown snow on the leeward side of a ridge or other sheltered area.  Wind slabs can form over weaker, softer freshly fallen powder snow, creating an avalanche hazard on steep slopes.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Sun or temperature-induced ====\n\n*''Firn'' \u2014 [[Firn]] is dense, granular snow, which has been in place for multiple years but which has not yet consolidated into [[Glacier#Formation|glacial ice]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_pCGDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&dq=firn+The+Physics+of+Glaciers#v=onepage&q=firn%20The%20Physics%20of%20Glaciers&f=false|title=The Physics of Glaciers|last=Paterson|first=W. S. B.|date=31 January 2017|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9781483293738|language=en}}</ref>\n*N\u00e9v\u00e9 \u2014 [[N\u00e9v\u00e9]] is a young, granular type of [[snow]] which has been partially melted, refrozen and compacted, yet precedes the form of ice.  This type of snow is associated with [[glacier]] formation through the process of [[nivation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.hofstra.edu/j_b_bennington/33notes/glaciers.html|title=Geol 33 Environmental Geomorphology|publisher=Hofstra University|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> N\u00e9v\u00e9 that survives a full season of [[ablation]] turns into [[firn]], which is both older and slightly denser.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*''Penitentes'' \u2014 [[Penitente (snow formation)|Penitentes]] are snow formations, found at high elevations, which form of elongated, thin blades of hardened snow or ice up to 5 meters in height, closely spaced and pointing towards the general direction of the sun. They are evolved suncups.<ref name=\"Lliboutry2\">{{cite journal|last1=Lliboutry|first1=L.|year=1954b|title=The origin of penitentes|url=|journal=Journal of Glaciology|volume=2|issue=15|pages=331\u2013338|doi=10.1017/S0022143000025181|accessdate=|bibcode=1954JGlac...2..331L|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*''Suncups'' \u2014 [[Suncup (snow)|Suncups]] are polygonal depressions in a [[snow]] surface that form patterns with sharp narrow ridges separating smoothly concave quasi-periodic hollows. They form during the [[ablation]] (melting away) of snow from [[Solar gain|incident solar radiation]] in bright [[Sunlight|sunny conditions]], sometimes enhanced by the insulating presence of dirt along the ridges.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R_Q6j8wsVqcC&pg=PA65&dq=%22sun+cups%22+snow#v=onepage&q=%22sun%20cups%22%20snow&f=false|title=Glaciers|last=Knight|first=Peter|date=13 May 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134982240|location=|pages=65|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Yukimarimo'' \u2014 [[Yukimarimo]] are balls of fine [[frost]], formed at low temperatures on the [[Antarctic Plateau]] during light or calm winds.<ref name=\"Kameda2007\">\n{{Cite journal\n|author =  T. Kameda\n|title = Discovery and reunion with yukimarimo\n|journal = Seppyo (Journal of Japanese Society of Snow and Ice)\n|year = 2007\n|volume = 69\n|number = 3\n|pages = 403\u2013407\n|url = http://homepage3.nifty.com/takaokameda/en/Kameda2007-AboutYukimarimo-inSeppyo.pdf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Ski resort classification===\nSki resorts use standardized terminology to describe their snow conditions. In North America terms include:<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7-HCBlUw6EMC&pg=PA26&dq=Packed+powder+snow#v=onepage&q=Packed%20powder%20snow&f=false|title=Handy Facts|last=Staff|date=January 1975|publisher=Ski|isbn=|location=|pages=42|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*''Base snow'' \u2014 Base snow refers to snow that has been thoroughly consolidated.\n*''Frozen granular'' \u2014 Frozen granular is snow whose granules have frozen together.\n*''Loose granular'' \u2014 Loose granular is snow with uncohesive granules.\n*''Machine-made'' \u2014 Machine-made snow is that produce by snow cannons and is typically denser than natural snow.\n*''New snow'' \u2014 New snow is that which has fallen since the previous day's report.\n*''Packed powder'' \u2014 Packed powder is powder snow that has been compressed by [[Snow grooming|grooming]] or by ski traffic.\n*''Powder'' \u2014 Powder is freshly fallen, uncompacted snow. The density and moisture content of powder snow can vary widely; snowfall in coastal regions and areas with higher humidity is usually heavier than a similar depth of snowfall in an arid or continental region. Light, dry (low moisture content, typically 4\u20137% water content) powder snow is prized by skiers and snowboarders.<ref name=\":5\" /> It is often found in the [[Rocky Mountains]] of North America and in most regions in Japan.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Spring conditions \u2014 Spring conditions describe a variety of melting snow surfaces, including mushy powder or granular snow, which refreeze at night.\n*''Wet'' \u2014 Wet refers to warm snow with a high moisture content.\n\n===Informal classification===\nSkiers and others living with snow provide informal terms for snow conditions that they encounter.\n*''Corn snow'' \u2014 Corn snow is coarse, granular snow, subject to freeze-thaw.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*''Crud'' \u2014 Crud covers varieties of snow that all but advanced skiers find impassable. Subtypes are (a) windblown powder with irregularly shaped crust patches and ridges, (b) heavy tracked spring snow re-frozen to leave a deeply rutted surface strewn with loose blocks, (c) a deep layer of heavy snow saturated by rain (although this may go by another term).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k-o-HmRiEFAC&pg=PA106&dq=crud+snow#v=onepage&q=crud%20snow&f=false|title=Crud: Stay light and centered on the edge|last=Delaney|first=Brian|date=January 1998|publisher=Snow Country|isbn=|location=|pages=106|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Packing snow'' \u2014 Packing snow is at or near the melting point, so that it can easily be packed into snowballs and thrown or used in the construction of a snowman, or a [[snow fort]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=How to build an igloo: And other snow shelters|last=Yankielun|first=Norbert|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Slush'' \u2014 [[Slush]] is substantially melted snow with visible water in it.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JyUXOeZzhAUC&pg=PA80&dq=Slush+snow#v=onepage&q=Slush%20snow&f=false|title=High-performance Skiing|last=Yacenda|first=John|last2=Ross|first2=Tim|date=1998|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=9780880117135|location=|pages=80\u201381|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Snirt'' \u2014 Snirt is an informal term for snow covered with dirt, especially where strong winds pick up topsoil from uncovered farm fields and blow it into nearby snowy areas. Also, dirty snow left over from plowing operations.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GwVQHza8fO8C&pg=PT119&dq=snirt+snow#v=onepage&q=snirt%20snow&f=false|title=Help! I'm Laughing and I Can't Get Up|last=Higgs|first=Liz Curtis|date=1998|publisher=HarperCollins Christian Publishing|isbn=9781418558758|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Spring snow'' \u2014 Spring snow describes a variety of temperature and moisture conditions with corn snow.<ref name=\":5\" />\n*''Watermelon snow'' \u2014 [[Watermelon snow]] is reddish pink, caused by a red-colored [[green algae]] called ''[[Chlamydomonas nivalis]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=William E. Williams|author2=Holly L. Gorton|author3=Thomas C. Vogelmann|last-author-amp=yes|date=21 January 2003|title=Surface gas-exchange processes of snow algae|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]]|volume=100|issue=2|pages=562\u2013566|bibcode=2003PNAS..100..562W|doi=10.1073/pnas.0235560100|pmc=141035|pmid=12518048}}</ref>\n\n==Other cultures==\n{{See also|Eskimo words for snow}}\nThe claim that [[Eskimo\u2013Aleut languages|Eskimoan languages]] (specifically, [[Yupik languages|Yupik]] and [[Inuit languages|Inuit]]) have an unusually large number of words for \"[[snow]]\", has been attributed to the work of [[anthropologist]] [[Franz Boas]].  Boas, who lived among Baffin islanders and learnt their language, reportedly included \"only words representing meaningful distinctions\" in his account.<ref name = \"Robson\"/> A 2010 study follows the sometimes questionable scholarship regarding the question whether Eskimo languages have many more [[root word]]s for \"snow\" than the English language.<ref>{{Citation\n | first = Igor\n | last = Krupnik\n | author-link =\n | first2 = Ludger \n | last2 = M\u00fcller-Wille\n | author2-link =\n | editor-last = Krupnik\n | editor-first = Igor\n | editor2-last = Aporta\n | editor2-first = Claudio\n | editor3-last = Gearheard\n | editor3-first = Shari\n | editor4-last = Laidler\n | editor4-first = Gita J.\n | editor5-last = Holm\n | editor5-first = Lene Kielsen\n | contribution = Franz Boas and Inuktitut Terminology for Ice and Snow: From the Emergence of the Field to the \u201cGreat Eskimo Vocabulary Hoax\u201d\n | contribution-url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226206215_Franz_Boas_and_Inuktitut_Terminology_for_Ice_and_Snow_From_the_Emergence_of_the_Field_to_the_Great_Eskimo_Vocabulary_Hoax\n | series =\n | year = 2010\n | pages = 377\u201399\n | place = Berlin\n | publisher = Springer Science & Business Media\n | title = SIKU: Knowing Our Ice: Documenting Inuit Sea Ice Knowledge and Use\n | doi =\n | isbn = 9789048185870}}.</ref><ref name=\"Robson\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg21628962-800-are-there-really-50-eskimo-words-for-snow/|title=Are there really 50 Eskimo words for snow?|last=Robson|first=David|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref>\n\nStudies of the [[Sami languages]] of Norway, Sweden and Finland, conclude that the languages have anywhere from 180 snow-and-ice-related words and as many as 300 different words for [[types of snow]], tracks in snow, and conditions of the use of snow.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Magga|first=Ole Henrik|date=March 2006|title=Diversity in Saami terminology for reindeer, snow, and ice|journal=International Social Science Journal|volume=58|issue=187|pages=25\u201334|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2451.2006.00594.x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berit|first=Inga|last2=\u00d6je|first2=Danell|title=Traditional ecological knowledge among Sami reindeer herders in northern Sweden about vascular plants grazed by reindeer|url=https://septentrio.uit.no/index.php/rangifer/article/viewFile/2233/2079|journal=Rangifer|volume=32|issue=1|pages=1\u201317|via=|doi=10.7557/2.32.1.2233|year=2013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|Glacier}}\n* {{annotated link|Ice}}\n* {{annotated link|METAR}} \u2014 a format for reporting weather information\n* {{annotated link|The wrong type of snow}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.canadianfieldnaturalist.ca/index.php/cfn/article/download/90/90.pdf Why and How to Study a Snowcover] \u2013 contains an extensive taxonomy of show terminology borrowed from Inuit and some other languages\n* Fierz, C., Armstrong, R.L., Durand, Y., Etchevers, P., Greene, E., McClung, D.M., Nishimura, K., Satyawali, P.K. and Sokratov, S.A.; [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0018/001864/186462e.pdf The International Classification for Seasonal Snow on the Ground]. IHP-VII Technical Documents in Hydrology N\u00b083, IACS Contribution N\u00b01, UNESCO-IHP, Paris, 2009.\n\n[[Category:Snow|*]]\n[[Category:Precipitation]]\n[[Category:Forms of water]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:SeeTemplate:Broader", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classifications_of_snow"}
{"title_page": "Thanga Magan (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thanga Magan\n| image          = Thanga magan.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| film name      = {{film name|Tamil|\u0ba4\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bae\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd}}\n| director       = [[Velraj]]\n| producer       = [[G. N. Anbu Chezhiyan]]\n| writer         = [[Velraj]]\n| starring       =  [[Dhanush]]<br>[[Samantha Ruth Prabhu]]<br>[[Amy Jackson]]\n| music          = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| cinematography = A. Kumaran\n| editing        = Rajesh Kumar\n| studio         = Gopuram Films\n| distributor    = Sri Green Productions<br/>[[Wunderbar Films]]\n| released       = 18 December 2015<ref>[http://www.sify.com/movies/dhanush-s-thanga-magan-sold-news-tamil-pktk4eagbjbif.html \"Dhanush's 'Thanga Magan' sold?\"] Sify.com. 19 October 2015.</ref>\n| budget         = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n}}\n'''''Thanga Magan''''' ({{translation|Golden Son}}) is a 2015 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Velraj]]. [[Dhanush]] produced and stars in the film alongside [[Samantha Ruth Prabhu]] and [[Amy Jackson]]. The film entered production in March 2015 and was released on 18 December 2015. The film released to mixed reviews but had a decent run at the box office.<ref>https://www.sify.com/movies/thangamagan-review--pmsncnbbfbidj.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThamizh ([[Dhanush]]) is a carefree youngster who lives with his dad ([[K. S. Ravikumar]]) and mom ([[Raadhika]]). Thamizh\u2019s best friends are Kumaran ([[Sathish]]) and cousin Aravind ([[Adith Arun]]) and they hang out all the time until Hema D\u2019Souza ([[Amy Jackson]]) enters the scene.\n\nIt is love-at-first sight for Thamizh but very soon a small misunderstanding separates the love birds and he marries Yamuna ([[Samantha Akkineni]]). Thamizh\u2019s life is complete and blissful till his father\u2019s suicide shatters him. Now the young man has a mission to find out the ugly truth behind his father's suicide.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Dhanush]] as Thamizh Vijayraghavan\n* [[Samantha Akkineni]] as Yamuna Thamizh, Thamizh's wife.\n* [[Amy Jackson]] as Hema D'Souza, Tamizh's first girlfriend and Aravind's wife.\n**[[Voiceover]] by [[Andrea Jeremiah]]\n* [[K. S. Ravikumar]] as Vijayraghavan, Thamizh's father\n* [[Raadhika]] as Thamizh's mother\n* [[Adith Arun]] as Aravind, Thamizh's cousin\n* [[Sathish]] as Kumaran, Thamizh's friend\n* [[Jayaprakash]] as Prakash Kumar, Thamizh's boss\n* [[M. S. Bhaskar]] as Prakash's assistant\n* [[Seetha (actress)|Seetha]] as Arvinth's mother\n* [[Shan (Tamil actor)|Shan]] as Varun\n* [[Uday Mahesh]] as Jen Builders agent\n* Poorthi Pravin as Revathi, Hema's friend\n* [[Velraj]] as Ramalingam (cameo appearance)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\nFollowing the success of ''[[Velaiilla Pattadhari]]'' (2014), [[Dhanush]] and [[Velraj]] announced that they would work together for another project during October 2014, and stated the film would not be a sequel to their previous film.<ref>[http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-14/the-vip-combo-is-back-dhanushs-next.html The VIP combo&nbsp;\u2013 Dhanush and Velraj, is back for another blockbuster?]. Behindwoods.com (15 October 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>  In December 2014, actress [[Amy Jackson]] revealed via [[Twitter]] that she had been signed on to feature in the film.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/dhanush-amy-jackson-to-team-up/article6658047.ece Dhanush, Amy Jackson to team up]. The Hindu (3 December 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> During the same month, [[Samantha Ruth Prabhu|Prabhu]] also joined the team, which reprised several crew members from the director's previous venture.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Samantha-joins-Dhanushs-VIP/articleshow/45657351.cms Samantha joins Dhanush's VIP&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (27 December 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> [[Sathish]] was selected to play a supporting role, while [[K. S. Ravikumar]] and [[Raadhika]] were signed on to play Dhanush's parents in the film.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/KS-Ravikumar-to-play-Dhanushs-dad/articleshow/47000648.cms KS Ravikumar to play Dhanush\u2019s dad?&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (22 April 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>\n\nThe team began production in March 2015 without a title, and the project remained untitled until October 2015, a month before the film's release.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Dhanush-joins-the-sets-of-Samanthas-film/articleshow/46642094.cms Dhanush joins the sets of Samantha's film&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (21 March 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> It developed under the working title of ''[[Velaiilla Pattadhari 2|VIP 2]]'', and the team denied reports of it being titled ''Tea Kadai Raja'' and ''Thamizh Magan'', before settling on ''Thanga Magan''.<ref>[http://www.uncutindia.com/dhanush-velrajs-next-to-be-titled-tea-kadai-raja/ Dhanush -Velraj's next to be titled 'Tea Kadai Raja']. Uncutindia.com (4 April 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> The first schedule involved Dhanush and Amy Jackson, with the former shaving his beard to appear as a teenager in the portions.<ref>[http://southie.in/dhanush-to-play-a-teenager-in-velraj-movie/ Dhanush to play a teenager in Velraj Movie.&nbsp;\u2013 Southie]. Southie.in. Retrieved on 27 November 2015.</ref> Scenes involving Samantha portraying Dhanush's wife were shot in May 2015, with the team recreating the effect of rainy backdrop in a studio in Chennai.<ref>[http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/dhanushs-next-film-vip-2-is-getting-canned-with-a-few-action-sequences.html Dhanush's next film VIP 2 is getting canned with a few action sequences]. Behindwoods.com (23 May 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> Amy Jackson finished work in the film in June 2015, after filming sequences alongside the other two lead actors.<ref>[http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/amy-jackson-to-wrap-up-dhanushs-vip-2.html Amy Jackson to wrap up Dhanush's VIP 2 soon]. Behindwoods.com (17 June 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> The film completed its final schedule in July 2015 by canning a fight scene and montage shots, without the presence of Velraj, who had to prioritise his work as a cinematographer for another film, ''[[Paayum Puli (2015 film)|Paayum Puli]]''. The director consequently denied reports that he had a fall out with the rest of the team.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/I-have-not-walked-out-of-Dhanushs-film-Velraj/articleshow/48173512.cms I have not walked out of Dhanush\u2019s film: Velraj&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (23 July 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Thangamagan\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 23 November 2015 <br>22 November 2015 (iTunes)\n| recorded     = 2015\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=13|s=44}}\n| label        = [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]]\n| producer     = Anirudh Ravichander\n| prev_title   = [[Vedalam]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = [[Remo (film)|Remo]]\n| next_year    = 2015\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack of the movie was composed by [[Anirudh Ravichander]] and was released on 23 November 2015. The [[Telugu language|Telugu]] version was released on 11 December 2015. \n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track listing\n| extra_column    = Singer(s)\n| total_length    = 13:44\n\n| title1          = Oh Oh\n| writer1         = Dhanush\n| extra1          = Dhanush & [[Nikhita Gandhi]]\n\n| length1         = 4:36\n| title2          = Enna Solla\n| writer2         = Dhanush\n| extra2          = [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = Tak Bak\n| writer3         = Dhanush\n| extra3          = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| length3         = 2:34\n| title4          = Jodi Nilave\n| writer4         = Dhanush\n| extra4          = Dhanush & [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length4         = 2:58\n}}\n\n;''Nava Manmadhudu'' (Telugu version)\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track listing\n| extra_column    = Singer(s)\n| total_length    = 13:44\n\n| title1          = Manasa Mansa\n| writer1         = Rakendu Mouli\n| extra1          = Dhanush & [[Sunitha Sarathy]]\n| length1         = 4:36\n| title2          = Emannavoo\n| writer2         = Vennelakanti\n| extra2          = [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = Nee Takari Look Ke\n| writer3         = Rakendu Mouli\n| extra3          = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| length3         = 2:34\n| title4          = Odini Lali\n| writer4         = Vennelakanti\n| extra4          = Dhanush & [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length4         = 2:58\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Thanga Magan'''s Tamil Nadu theatrical rights were sold to Sri Green Productions. The film was released on 18 December 2015.<ref>[http://www.sify.com/movies/dhanush-s-thanga-magan-sold-news-tamil-pktk4eagbjbif.html \"Dhanush's 'Thanga Magan' sold?\"] Sify.com. 19 October 2015.</ref> The film was dubbed and released in Telugu as ''Nava Manmadhudu''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telangananewspaper.com/nava-manmadhudu-2015-wiki-audio-songs-release/ |title=Nava Manmadhudu 2015 Movie Details |date=13 November 2015 |author=TNP =TelanganaNewsPaper}}</ref> The satellite rights of ''Thanga Magan'' were sold to [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]].<ref>http://www.cinemaone.in/sun-tv-telecast-thanga-magan-premier-movie-18th-september-2016/</ref>\n\nThe film was also dubbed and released in Hindi as ''Paap Ki Kamai'' in 2019.\n\n===Critical reception===\n''[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA India]]'' rated the film 3 stars and said, \"Watch the movie for the fine performances by the lead actors.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-thanga-magan-review-the-fine-performances-by-dhanush-samantha-and-amy-jackson-make-it-a-must-watch-2157344 | title='Thanga Magan' review: The fine performances by Dhanush, Samantha and Amy Jackson make it a must-watch | publisher= DNA India | accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref> [[Filmibeat]] rated the film 3.0/5 and said, \"''Thanga Magan'', though not as impressive as ''Velaiyilla Pattathari'', manages to make you laugh and weep. It also most definitely, entertains you.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/reviews/2015/thanga-magan-movie-review-and-rating-story-plot-dhanush-glitters-208876.html | title=Thanga Magan Movie Review And Rating: Dhanush Glitters Throughout!| publisher= Filmibeat | accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref> OnlyKollywood rated ''Thanga Magan'' 2.75 out of 5 and added, \"''Thanga Magan'' offers rollicking fun in its simplistic, chocolate-box romance portions though its modus operandi appears plain and unequivocal in the way the familial relations are staged, especially in the second half.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onlykollywood.com/thanga-magan-movie-review/ |title=Thanga-Magan-Review |publisher=OnlyKollywood |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222021216/http://www.onlykollywood.com/thanga-magan-movie-review/ |archivedate=22 December 2015 |url-status=live |accessdate=21 June 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''Behindwoods'' rated the film 2.5 out of 5 and wrote, \"On the whole, ''Thanga Magan'' does justice to its cause, which is to entertain, but doesn't keep the audience engrossed.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/thangamagan/thangamagan-review.html|title=Thanga Magan Review | publisher=Behindwoods| accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref> Tamilglitz rated the film 2.5 out of 5 and called it \"a simple movie which is worth [watching]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bala |first=Rahul |url=https://tamilglitz.in/thanga-magan-thangamagan-movie-review-dhanush/ |title=Thanga Magan (Thangamagan) Movie Review &#124; Dhanush - TamilGlitz |website=Tamilglitz.in |date=2015-12-18 |accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=5124096}}\n{{Wunderbar Films}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Anirudh Ravichander]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian family films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thanga Magan\n| image          = Thanga magan.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| film name      = {{film name|Tamil|\u0ba4\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bae\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd}}\n| director       = [[Velraj]]\n| producer       = [[G. N. Anbu Chezhiyan]]\n| writer         = [[Velraj]]\n| starring       =  [[Dhanush]]<br>[[Samantha Ruth Prabhu]]<br>[[Amy Jackson]]\n| music          = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| cinematography = A. Kumaran\n| editing        = Rajesh Kumar\n| studio         = Gopuram Films\n| distributor    = Sri Green Productions<br/>[[Wunderbar Films]]\n| released       = 18 December 2015<ref>[http://www.sify.com/movies/dhanush-s-thanga-magan-sold-news-tamil-pktk4eagbjbif.html \"Dhanush's 'Thanga Magan' sold?\"] Sify.com. 19 October 2015.</ref>\n| budget         = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n}}\n'''''Thanga Magan''''' ({{translation|Golden Son}}) is a 2015 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Velraj]]. [[Dhanush]] produced and stars in the film alongside [[Samantha Ruth Prabhu]] and [[Amy Jackson]]. The film entered production in March 2015 and was released on 18 December 2015. The film released to mixed reviews but had a decent run at the box office.<ref>https://www.sify.com/movies/thangamagan-review--pmsncnbbfbidj.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThamizh ([[Dhanush]]) is a carefree youngster who lives with his dad ([[K. S. Ravikumar]]) and mom ([[Raadhika]]). Thamizh\u2019s best friends are Kumaran ([[Sathish]]) and cousin Aravind ([[Adith Arun]]) and they hang out all the time until Hema D\u2019Souza ([[Amy Jackson]]) enters the scene.\n\nIt is love-at-first sight for Thamizh but very soon a small misunderstanding separates the love birds and he gets married to Yamuna ([[Samantha Akkineni]]). Thamizh\u2019s life is complete and blissful till his dad\u2019s suicide shatters him. Now the young man has a mission to find out the ugly truth behind his dad's suicide.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Dhanush]] as Thamizh Vijayraghavan\n* [[Samantha Akkineni]] as Yamuna Thamizh, Thamizh's wife.\n* [[Amy Jackson]] as Hema D'Souza, Tamizh's first girlfriend and Aravind's wife.\n**[[Voiceover]] by [[Andrea Jeremiah]]\n* [[K. S. Ravikumar]] as Vijayraghavan, Thamizh's father\n* [[Raadhika]] as Thamizh's mother\n* [[Adith Arun]] as Aravind, Thamizh's cousin\n* [[Sathish]] as Kumaran, Thamizh's friend\n* [[Jayaprakash]] as Prakash Kumar, Thamizh's boss\n* [[M. S. Bhaskar]] as Prakash's assistant\n* [[Seetha (actress)|Seetha]] as Arvinth's mother\n* [[Shan (Tamil actor)|Shan]] as Varun\n* [[Uday Mahesh]] as Jen Builders Agent\n* Poorthi Pravin as Revathi, Hema's friend\n* [[Velraj]] as Ramalingam (cameo appearance)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\nFollowing the success of ''[[Velaiilla Pattadhari]]'' (2014), [[Dhanush]] and [[Velraj]] announced that they would work together for another project during October 2014, and stated the film would not be a sequel to their previous film.<ref>[http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-14/the-vip-combo-is-back-dhanushs-next.html The VIP combo&nbsp;\u2013 Dhanush and Velraj, is back for another blockbuster?]. Behindwoods.com (15 October 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>  In December 2014, actress [[Amy Jackson]] revealed via [[Twitter]] that she had been signed on to feature in the film.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/dhanush-amy-jackson-to-team-up/article6658047.ece Dhanush, Amy Jackson to team up]. The Hindu (3 December 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> During the same month, [[Samantha Ruth Prabhu|Prabhu]] also joined the team, which reprised several crew members from the director's previous venture.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Samantha-joins-Dhanushs-VIP/articleshow/45657351.cms Samantha joins Dhanush's VIP&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (27 December 2014). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> [[Sathish]] was selected to play a supporting role, while [[K. S. Ravikumar]] and [[Raadhika]] were signed on to play Dhanush's parents in the film.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/KS-Ravikumar-to-play-Dhanushs-dad/articleshow/47000648.cms KS Ravikumar to play Dhanush\u2019s dad?&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (22 April 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>\n\nThe team began production in March 2015 without a title, and the project remained untitled until October 2015, a month before the film's release.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Dhanush-joins-the-sets-of-Samanthas-film/articleshow/46642094.cms Dhanush joins the sets of Samantha's film&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (21 March 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> It developed under the working title of ''[[Velaiilla Pattadhari 2|VIP 2]]'', and the team denied reports of it being titled ''Tea Kadai Raja'' and ''Thamizh Magan'', before settling on ''Thanga Magan''.<ref>[http://www.uncutindia.com/dhanush-velrajs-next-to-be-titled-tea-kadai-raja/ Dhanush -Velraj's next to be titled 'Tea Kadai Raja']. Uncutindia.com (4 April 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> The first schedule involved Dhanush and Amy Jackson, with the former shaving his beard to appear as a teenager in the portions.<ref>[http://southie.in/dhanush-to-play-a-teenager-in-velraj-movie/ Dhanush to play a teenager in Velraj Movie.&nbsp;\u2013 Southie]. Southie.in. Retrieved on 27 November 2015.</ref> Scenes involving Samantha portraying Dhanush's wife were shot in May 2015, with the team recreating the effect of rainy backdrop in a studio in Chennai.<ref>[http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/dhanushs-next-film-vip-2-is-getting-canned-with-a-few-action-sequences.html Dhanush's next film VIP 2 is getting canned with a few action sequences]. Behindwoods.com (23 May 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> Amy Jackson finished work in the film in June 2015, after filming sequences alongside the other two lead actors.<ref>[http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/amy-jackson-to-wrap-up-dhanushs-vip-2.html Amy Jackson to wrap up Dhanush's VIP 2 soon]. Behindwoods.com (17 June 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref> The film completed its final schedule in July 2015 by canning a fight scene and montage shots, without the presence of Velraj, who had to prioritise his work as a cinematographer for another film, ''[[Paayum Puli (2015 film)|Paayum Puli]]''. The director consequently denied reports that he had a fall out with the rest of the team.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/I-have-not-walked-out-of-Dhanushs-film-Velraj/articleshow/48173512.cms I have not walked out of Dhanush\u2019s film: Velraj&nbsp;\u2013 The Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (23 July 2015). Retrieved on 2015-11-27.</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Thangamagan\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 23 November 2015 <br>22 November 2015 (iTunes)\n| recorded     = 2015\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=13|s=44}}\n| label        = [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]]\n| producer     = Anirudh Ravichander\n| prev_title   = [[Vedalam]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = [[Remo (film)|Remo]]\n| next_year    = 2015\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack of the movie was composed by [[Anirudh Ravichander]] and was released on 23 November 2015. The [[Telugu language|Telugu]] version was released on 11 December 2015. \n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track listing\n| extra_column    = Singer(s)\n| total_length    = 13:44\n\n| title1          = Oh Oh\n| writer1         = Dhanush\n| extra1          = Dhanush & [[Nikhita Gandhi]]\n\n| length1         = 4:36\n| title2          = Enna Solla\n| writer2         = Dhanush\n| extra2          = [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = Tak Bak\n| writer3         = Dhanush\n| extra3          = [[Anirudh Ravichander]]\n| length3         = 2:34\n| title4          = Jodi Nilave\n| writer4         = Dhanush\n| extra4          = Dhanush & [[Shweta Mohan]]\n| length4         = 2:58\n}}\n\n;''Nava Manmadhudu'' (Telugu version)\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Track 